Okobolo, which was subsequently transcribed, translated, and edited by the renowned Nigerian poet, playwright, and scholar John Pepper Clark-Bekederemo. The study concludes with a look at the work of contemporary Nigerian creative writers and their connection to the powerful literary and historical currents of the Ozidi story. Isidore Okpewho is Distinguished Professor of Africana Studies, English, and Comparative Literature at Binghamton University (SUNY). He is the author of The Epic in Africa, Myth in Africa, African Oral Literature, and Once upona Kingdom. An award-winning novelist, he has published four titles: The Victims, The Last Duty, Tides, and Call Me by My Rightful Name.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFolk literature, AfricanxHistory and criticism. 0aIjo (African people)zNigeriaxFolklore. 0aIjo (African people)zNigeriaxSocial life and customs. 0aOral traditionzNigeria. 4aAfrican Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / African.2bisacsh  aBlood on the Tides: The Ozidi Saga and Oral Epic Narratology.  aDelta region of Nigeria.  aJohn Pepper Clark-Bekederemo.  aNigerian Delta.  aOzidi Saga.  aOzidi story.  acontemporary Nigerian creative writers.  afolk artist.  aoral literature.  asocial and political concerns.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2014z978311143136940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978158046847340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781580468473423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781580468473/original  a978-3-11-143136-9  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2014b2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles